<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1205,1338]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1205,1230]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Comments.</emphasis>
This is the only species in the 
<taxonomicName box="[676,814,1205,1229]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Howickia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trilineata">
<emphasis box="[676,814,1205,1229]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">H. trilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group with a posteromedial comb. The surstylus of this species is distinctive, and leaves no doubt about its validity although it is known from only a single specimen. The terminalia suggest that this species is more closely related to the 
<taxonomicName box="[872,981,1278,1301]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Howickia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="myersi">
<emphasis box="[872,981,1278,1301]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">H. myersi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group than the 
<taxonomicName box="[1154,1292,1277,1301]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Howickia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trilineata">
<emphasis box="[1154,1292,1277,1301]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">H. trilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, but it is grouped with the latter because of the distinctively striped head.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
